class:: TapeCh
summary:: Nonlinear tape stage based on the ChowTape module
categories:: UGens>Effects
related:: Guides/ChowDSPPorts

Description::

TapeCh follows the standalone nonlinear stage from ChowTape. The core DSP is the original hysteresis model solved with the `NR4` method at fixed 4x oversampling, so the output depends on both the current sample and the evolving magnetic state of the model rather than only on a static saturation curve. In mathematical terms it is a stateful nonlinear system with memory, which is the right kind of model for tape because magnetization depends on recent excitation history.

That is why tape saturation tends to feel smoother and more cumulative than ordinary clipping. Bias changes the operating point, `saturation` changes how easily the virtual medium bends into compression, and `drive` determines how hard the signal pushes the model. The result ranges from subtle thickening to obvious soft crunch and low-level dynamic flattening.

definitionlist::
## bias: || normalized `0..1` control mapped to the hysteresis width parameter as `1 - bias`
## saturation: || normalized `0..1` saturation control used directly by the hysteresis model
## drive: || normalized `0..1` drive control used directly by the hysteresis model
::

Like the Rack module, the input is normalized from `+/- 5 V` to `+/- 1` before processing. The current Rack source configures a DC blocker but does not actually route the signal through it, so this standalone port preserves that behavior instead of silently changing the nonlinear stage.

classmethods::

method::ar

argument::in
Input signal.

argument::bias
Normalized bias control in `0..1`.

argument::saturation
Normalized saturation control in `0..1`.

argument::drive
Normalized drive control in `0..1`.

argument::mul
Output multiplier.

argument::add
Output offset.


